{"id": "1701dac9-f25c-4639-ac38-6ac9ccc1aec5", "value": "The calcareous material is first washed with deionized water, removing associated organic sediments and debris, where present. The material for radiocarbon dating is then crushed/dispersed and repeatedly subjected to HCl etches to eliminate secondary carbonate components.

shell samples for AMS Carbon-14 DatingIn the case of thick shells, the surfaces are physically abraded prior to etching until the hard, primary core remains. In the case of porous carbonate nodules and caliche, very long exposure times are applied to allow infiltration of the acid. Acid exposure times, concentrations, and number of repetitions are applied according to the uniqueness of the sample.

Typically applied to – shells, caliche, calcareous nodules"}
